>CJD AND BLOOD DONORS (02)
>=========================
>
>The World Health Organization will recommend barring "groups of higher risk
of having Creutfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) from donating blood." The decision
is taken in the light of scientific evidence suggesting a link between BSE
and nvCJD.
>
I doubt that this is "in the light of scientific evidence suggesting a
link between BSE and nvCJD". If so it would be a stupid decision. It is
almost certainly in the light that:
>People treated with contaminated growth hormone early in the 1980s; people
who have had brain or other surgery in which duramater was used to patch
tissue; and families of CJD sufferers
>
In which case this post has no place here, being misleading at best.
>"While experts determined they have no proof that CJD can be transmitted
via blood transfusions, they said there is a potential risk", according to
Financial Times (03/27/97)
>
And the numbers of people restricted is probably no more than a few
hundred worldwide.
>----- Now, consider this:
>
>* In the perspective of a potentially huge BSE exposure to humans in the
>UK, mostly during the 80's
>
>* That nvCJD may have a general incubation period of several decades
>
>* And that the blood supply in the UK and elsewhere are not screened for CJD
>
>*** I suggest that all blood products from the UK should be recognized by
the international community as potentially risky. At least until a
satisfying test can be used to identify the infectious agent in blood products.
>
Excellent idea. Since it's donated free of charge why should it go
elsewhere? This decision might well reduce the importation of blood
products from countries that pay for it, often to drug abusers and very
poor (and potentially infected with many other things) people.
>*** There is currently "no proof that CJD can be transmitted via blood
transfusions", but there is a "potential risk".
>
Yup. Plenty of other things where the risk is not 'potential' but actual
and I rate them several orders of magnitude more likely to be
transmitted.
>Therefore, I also suggest that bovine blood, as well as beef products
including blood, should be recognized as potentially risky. Especially
bovine blood and beef products from countries with high BSE numbers.
>
Fear not, only the Brits are allowed to eat British beef, including
'blood products' whatever they are. Due to the 30 month culling rule I
have never known it so good (except for hamburger joints that import old
cow beef from Argentina). It's all young, tender and delicious. This is
just as well since my family and I are just about to eat a big piece of
sirloin for my Easter sunday joint. Nice and red and bloody on the
inside such that you can only do with young tender animals. Bon appetit!
---
O. Hotz de Baar
Farmer, Southern England, UK.
